"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61197","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-16","<p /> <p /> <p>The information requested on the duration of benefit sanctions is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The available information on the number of individuals with an adverse benefit sanction is shown in the table below.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Number of individuals with an adverse benefit sanction in Warrington Jobcentre Plus office: 2010 – 2013</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Jobseeker's Allowance (JSA)</p></td><td><p>Employment and Support Allowance (ESA)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>1,121</p></td><td><p>146</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>912</p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>1,436</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1,488</p></td><td><p>55</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: DWP Information, Governance and Security Directorate: Sanctions and Disallowance Decisions Statistics Database.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p>1. Statistical disclosure control has been applied to protect against the identification of individual claimants.</p><p>2. Figures for Income Support Lone Parents are not available by Jobcentre Plus office.</p><p>3. The number of benefit sanctions applied is the number of sanction or disallowance referrals where the decision was found against the claimant.</p><p>4. Data refers to January to December in each year shown.</p><p>5. New regulations introduced a new revised sanctions regime for JSA and ESA claimants from 22<sup>nd</sup> October and 3<sup>rd </sup>December 2012 respectively.</p><p>6. This data is published at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-06-16T10:55:29.0543826Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61197/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61197/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-10","Social Security Benefits: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in receipt of each type of benefit were sanctioned and for what period by Warrington Jobcentre in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","200048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61198","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-06-16","<p>All 39 Local Enterprise Partnerships' Growth Deals are currently being assessed, including requests for local growth funding, and we are looking to make announcements in the summer.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-06-16T10:16:12.8535835Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61198/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61198/answer",,,,,,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-06-10","Coast to Capital Local Enterprise Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what assessment he has made of the request for local growth funding by the Coast to Capital LEP; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","200045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61199","Department for Education","false","2014-06-18","<p>Academies can only change their admission arrangements following the procedures set out in the School Admissions Code.</p><p> </p><p>During the 2013/14 academic year the Education Funding Agency has received requests to change admissions arrangements for 8 academies. Of these, 7 were approved and 1 was withdrawn by the academy trust.</p><p> </p><p>These figures do not include applications to change admissions arrangements that form part of a request for a wider change to an academy's funding agreement, for example extending the age range, as this data is not recorded centrally.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-06-18T15:20:17.7185138Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61199/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61199/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-10","Academies: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applications his Department has received from academies seeking to change their admissions policies; and how many such applications his Department accepted.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","199854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61200","Department for Education","false","2014-06-18","<p>The Department does not hold records about the number of local authorities that operate three-tier systems.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-06-18T13:37:07.4874981Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61200/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61200/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-10","Local Education Authorities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many local education authorities currently operate a three-tier system; how many such authorities have sought to change to a two-tier system since 2010; and how many such authorities have changed to a two-tier system.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","199852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61201","Department for Education","false","2014-06-18","<p>There are 190 schools in England that are recorded on Edubase, the Department's database of education providers, as being middle schools. Of these, 59 are converter academies and three are sponsored academies.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-06-18T13:35:58.9359386Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61201/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61201/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-10","Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many middle schools there are in England; and how many of those schools are academies.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","199853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61202","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-06-18","<p>The Government has no plans at this time to extend the power of recall beyond Members of Parliament.</p><p> </p>","Sheffield, Hallam","Mr Nick Clegg",,"2014-06-18T15:45:00.8757255Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61202/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Clegg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61202/answer",,,,,,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-06-10","Members: Conduct","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, whether recall powers for local elected representatives will be included in the Government's Bill to enable recall of hon. Members.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","199851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61203","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-18","<p> </p><p>The report produced for the Department at the end of the study (Ref: M. Clark, P. Sayer, <em>Euro 3 LPG Retrofit Emissions Factor Testing</em>, Tickford Powertrain Test Ltd., ER07/015, June 2007) contains the data captured by the testing. Copies of the report will be placed in the in the Libraries of the House.</p><p> </p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2014-06-18T12:44:45.8586364Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61203/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61203/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-10","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 8 May 2014, Official Report, column 276W, on motor vehicles: exhaust emissions, if he will place the data from his Department's 2006 study of liquefied petroleum and petrol vehicles in the Library.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","200008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61204","Department of Health","false","2014-06-16","<p>On behalf of the Department, the Health and Social Care Information Centre (HSCIC) has commissioned the “What about Youth?” trial survey to test the processes and methodology. It was carried out by Ipsos Mori and ran from November 2013 to February 2014. The trial survey was posted to just under 7,000 younger people using information obtained from the Medical Research Information Service Integrated Database and Administration System, approval for which was obtained on 15 August 2013 via the HSCIC Data Linkage and Extract Services application process:</p><p> </p><p>http://www.hscic.gov.uk/dlesaac</p><p> </p><p>The decision to approve the request for provision of an extract will be included in the next Data Release Register due in early July.</p><p> </p><p>The National Pupil Database (NPD) is a Department for Education resource. HSCIC gained approval to use NPD data by applying via the formal process:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/national-pupil-database-apply-for-a-data-extract#approval-process</p><p> </p><p>and received approval to use NPD for the trial survey on 18 March 2014; however, this was too late for the trial and the data were not used. Ipsos Mori was granted access to the extract on 10 April. The decision to approve the request for provision of an extract is shown on row 139 of the “National pupil database: requests received” at:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-pupil-database-requests-received</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-06-16T13:41:17.7966826Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61204/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61204/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-06-10","Medical Records: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the statement on the What About Youth? website that approval has been received to use young people's contact details from NHS registration data and the National Pupil Database, when that data was supplied; and on what register the decision to disclose that data was recorded.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","200053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61205","Department of Health","false","2014-06-16","<p>I refer the hon. Members to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Truro and Falmouth (Sarah Newton) on 9 June 2014, <em>Official Report</em>, column 57W.</p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","200156","2014-06-16T14:24:21.5338076Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61205/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61205/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-06-10","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Answer of 18 March 2014, Official Report, column 572W, on mental health services: children, when he expects NHS England's review of Tier 4 Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services to be published.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","200127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61206","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-06-16","<p>As a permanent member of the Security Council, the UK is a leading advocate of ensuring that protection of civilians from violence is prioritised in the mandates of UN Missions working in conflict-affected countries. UN Security Council Resolution 2155 of 27 May 2014, which renewed UNMISS's mandate (and which the UK fully supported) demonstrates that, including through requiring UNMISS troops to conduct regular patrols to safeguard the security of communities within high risk areas. It also provides for civilian expertise to support and complement the work of the military troops and formed police units in monitoring and investigating human rights abuses</p>","Boston and Skegness","Mark Simmonds",,"2014-06-16T08:49:26.0253632Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61206/answer","Biography information for Mark Simmonds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61206/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-06-10","South Sudan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to ensure that UNMISS protects civilians by (a) regular patrols and consultation with communities and (b) involvement of civilians experts in UNMISS programmes.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","200140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61207","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-06-16","<p>The Governments of both Sudan and South Sudan have now granted the necessary clearances for the transfer of a Rwandan battalion from the UN-Africa Union Mission in Darfur (UNAMID) to UNMISS. We understand that that battalion has now arrived in South Sudan.</p><p>We have made clear to the Governments of both Sudan and South Sudan that any actions that impede UNMISS in the delivery of its mandate are unacceptable.</p>","Boston and Skegness","Mark Simmonds",,"2014-06-16T08:46:38.1515274Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61207/answer","Biography information for Mark Simmonds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61207/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-06-10","South Sudan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to help ensure that the government of Sudan facilitates the full deployment of UNMISS troops and equipment.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","200139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61208","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-03","<p>Data held centrally on prisoners transferred to open prisons does not distinguish between different types of indeterminate sentenced prisoner. Indeterminate sentences include those serving mandatory, discretionary and automatic life sentences and those serving Imprisonment for Public Protection (IPP) sentences.</p><p> </p><p>Identifying which prisoners were serving life sentences would require a manual trawl of records, which would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-07-03T16:20:33.684202Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61208/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61208/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-10","Life Imprisonment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many life sentence prisoners were moved into open prisons in each month between January 2010 and December 2013.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","200046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61209","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-14","<p>In a joint statement with the Bar Council, the Criminal Bar Association and the Circuit Leaders, the Ministry of Justice has confirmed that normal working relationships have been restored and there is no need to expand the PDS Advocacy Unit further.</p><p> </p><p>As at 10th July 2014, the following Barristers have commenced employment with the PDS:</p><p> </p><p><strong>Queens Counsel</strong></p><p>David Aubrey QC</p><p>Gregory Bull QC</p><p>John Burton QC</p><p>Alun Jenkins QC</p><p>Andrew Lamb QC</p><p>Stephen Leslie QC</p><p>Michael Wood QC</p><p> </p><p><strong>Juniors</strong></p><p>Lisa Hennessey</p><p>Robin Howat</p><p>Tom Mitchell</p><p>Gerald Mohabir</p><p>Emma Nott</p><p>Simon Perkins</p><p>Adam Roxborough</p><p>Martin L. Sharpe</p><p>Peter Woodall</p><p>George Zachary</p><p>As employed Barristers no day rates are charged for work done.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-14T12:57:11.9262971Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61209/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61209/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-10","Public Defender Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which barristers are employed by the Public Defence Service; and what day rates each such person charges.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","200015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61210","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-14","<p>Since January 2014 the PDS has employed the following number of Barristers (Full Time Equivalent):</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>January 2014</p></td><td><p>0.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February 2014</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2014</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2014</p></td><td><p>4.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2014</p></td><td><p>6.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-14T12:58:43.8756494Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61210/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61210/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-10","Public Defender Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many barristers have been employed by the Public Defence Service in each month since January 2014.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","200016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61211","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-14","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>£15,494.72 has been spent on advertising vacancies within the PDS in 2014. This includes vacancies for Accredited Police Station Representatives as well as for Queens Counsel and Higher Courts Advocates.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-14T13:00:09.8787958Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61211/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61211/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-10","Public Defender Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much has been spent on advertising vacancies in the Public Defence Service in 2014.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","200017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61212","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-14","<table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Jan</p></td><td><p>Feb</p></td><td><p>Mar</p></td><td><p>Apr</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Total Monthly Expenditure</p></td><td><p>£174,484</p></td><td><p>£229,646</p></td><td><p>£362,060</p></td><td><p>£268,849</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The rise in cost over the periods January to April is due to the recruitment of advocates in readiness for the PDS Advocacy service, and the inclusion of accruals in March for costs relating to IT enhancements and facilities management.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-14T14:13:12.9806059Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61212/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61212/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-10","Public Defender Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much has been spent on the Public Defence Service in each month of 2014.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","200018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61213","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-06-17","<p>Since September 2011, the customers of RBS, Ulster Bank, and NatWest have been able to withdraw cash free of charge at all post office branches across the UK. With around 11,700 branches – more branches than all the high street banks and building societies combined – the Post Office is the largest retail network in the UK. It is also the only retail network that meets the Government's strict access criteria that see, for example, 99% of the national population live within three miles of an outlet. With 95% of all UK debit card holders able to access cash at Post Office counters, the Post Office is in many communities the only source of free to access cash.</p><p>The Post Office is also a major provider of personal financial services. In partnership with its banking partner, the Post Office provides a wide range of financial services including mortgages, credit cards, and savings products. The Post Office is currently trialling its own current account products.</p>","Cardiff Central","Jenny Willott",,"2014-06-17T13:18:26.6283239Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61213/answer","Biography information for Jenny Willott","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61213/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-06-10","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make representations to RBS and all its subsidiaries on making their services available at post offices.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","199826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61214","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-17","<p> </p><p>The make, model, place of manufacture and cost of purchase or lease for cars procured formerly by the Government Car and Despatch Agency and latterly by the Government Car Service since the 6 May 2010 are set out in the following table. The current Government Car Service fleet is comprised of 85 cars, reduced from 227 cars as at 31March 2010.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2014-06-17T15:55:16.6405033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61214/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61214/answer","199983 - Government Car Service fleet - table.doc","199983 - Government Car Service fleet - table.doc","Table of Government Car Service fleet","Table of Government Car Service fleet","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61214/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-10","Official Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer to the hon. Member for Dudley North of 22 June 2010, Official Report, column 113W, on the Government Car and Dispatch Agency, what the (a) make, (b) model and (c) place of manufacture was of each car (i) purchased and (ii) leased by the Government Car Service since 6 May 2010; and how much each such car cost to purchase or lease.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","199983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61215","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-06-17","<p>The current negotiations with Iran are the best opportunity in years to resolve the issue of Iran's nuclear programme. Negotiations so far, which have built on the Geneva interim deal, have been constructive, but challenging: any deal will require Iran to take significant steps to address comprehensively our proliferation concerns. However, there remains commitment on all sides of the table to reach a deal.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Hugh Robertson",,"2014-06-17T08:17:01.6104101Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61215/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugh Robertson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61215/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-06-10","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of prospects for successful negotiations with Iran over its nuclear programme.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","199835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61216","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-16","<p>Staffing levels are a matter for the train operator, as long as they continue to deliver services that meet the requirements of the Franchise Agreement.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2014-06-16T15:48:59.2754696Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61216/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61216/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-10","London Midland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will assess the potential effects on (a) industrial relations, (b) rail passenger services and (c) rail franchising policy of London Midland's staffing proposals.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","200149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61217","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-16","<p> </p><p>London Midland is not currently in receipt of revenue support. Unless revenue was to fall to such an extent that they were to be eligible for such payments, the revenue during this franchise term is entirely its risk. London Midland has assured us that their staff restructuring plans will not prevent them fulfilling their obligations in meeting the requirements of the Franchise Agreement. Therefore, unless revenue was to fall to the extent that London Midland were eligible for revenue support payments, no further assessment is planned.</p><p> </p><p />","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2014-06-16T15:53:01.8296219Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61217/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61217/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-10","London Midland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will assess the potential effect on levels of passenger ticket revenue of London Midland's proposal to reduce the number of revenue protection staff.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","200148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61218","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-16","<p>Govia have made us aware of their staffing restructuring plans and the reasoning behind them. They have also provided assurances that these plans will not prevent them from fulfilling their obligations in meeting the requirements of the Franchise Agreement.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2014-06-16T15:50:55.6453804Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61218/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61218/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-10","London Midland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with representatives from Govia on its plan to reduce the number of revenue protection staff working on the London Midland line; what reasons he has been given by Govia for those reductions.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","200150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61219","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-16","<p>The Operational Research Computerised Allocation of Tickets to Services (ORCATS) is owned by Rail Settlement Plan Ltd, a company administered by the Association of Train Operating Companies and wholly-owned by the Train Operating Companies collectively. It is one of the means of allocating revenue. Under the Ticketing Settlement Agreement, ORCATS is the default allocation method used in respect of any ticket type and flow. However, it is not mandatory, and Train Operating Companies are free to agree a non-ORCATS allocation in respect of particular ticket types and/or flows if they think that the ORCATS model will not produce a fair estimate of true passenger behaviour.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2014-06-16T15:52:38.4045492Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61219/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61219/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-10","London Midland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the existing contractual obligations to share ticket revenue with other train operating companies through the Operational Research Computerised Allocation of Tickets to Services system in the current franchise agreement between his Department and Govia for passenger rail services on the London Midland line.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","200151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61220","Department for Transport","false","2014-06-16","<p> </p><p>Staffing levels and to which role staff are allocated are matters for the train operator, as long as they continue to deliver the services that meet the requirements of the Franchise Agreement.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2014-06-16T15:51:47.3341005Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61220/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61220/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-06-10","London Midland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will assess the potential effect on gateline staffing levels at (a) Birmingham New Street, (b) Coventry and (c) all stations on the London Midland line of London Midland's proposals to reduce the number of revenue protection staff.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","200147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61221","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-06-16","<p> </p><p>Information on students awarded and paid Disabled Students' Allowance is published annually by Student Loans Company (SLC) in the Statistical First Release ‘<em>Student Support for Higher Education England</em>'. The latest statistics are available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/media/694170/slcsfr052013.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/media/694170/slcsfr052013.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A further breakdown for Nottingham South constituency, Nottingham LEA and the East Midlands has been provided in the table for the academic year 2012/13. Equivalent figures for the academic year 2013/14 will be available from November 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Students in receipt of Disabled Students Allowance<sup>[1]</sup> from Nottingham South constituency, Nottingham and the East Midlands</strong></p><p> </p><p>Academic Year 2012/13</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td colspan="4"><p>Application Type</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><p>Full-Time Application</p></td><td><p>Part-Time Application</p></td><td><p>Post Graduate DSA</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(Area)</p></td><td><p>No of Applicants Paid</p></td><td><p>No of Applicants Paid</p></td><td><p>No of Applicants Paid</p></td><td><p>No of Applicants Paid</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands Government Region<sup>[2]</sup></p></td><td><p>4,320</p></td><td><p>180</p></td><td><p>330</p></td><td><p>4,830</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nottingham LEA<sup>[2]</sup></p></td><td><p>280</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>330</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nottingham South Constituency<sup>[2]</sup></p></td><td><p>80</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Effective date: 13/11/2013</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><p>[1] Disabled Student Allowance may be paid to the Student or to a Supplier on the student's behalf.</p><p> </p><p>[2] Figures are derived from the Post Code of the applicant's home address.</p><p> </p><p>[3] The effective date is that of the November 2013 Awards Statistical First Release. The figures are therefore provisional and do not include students who were awarded DSA after November 2013.</p><p> </p><p>[4] DSA Payments may be made at any point during the Academic Year or after the end of the Academic Year.</p><p> </p><p>[5] Numbers are rounded to the nearest 10. Totals may not add to the sum of the components due to rounding.</p><p> </p><p>[6] '-' represents a number less than 5.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Havant","Mr David Willetts",,"2014-06-16T16:07:05.5441824Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61221/answer","Biography information for Lord Willetts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61221/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-06-10","Disabled Students' Allowances: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many recipients of disabled students' allowance there are in (a) Nottingham South, (b) Nottingham and (c) the East Midlands.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","199832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61222","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-16","<p> </p><p>No assessment has been made of the annual cost of maintaining existing pension provisions for firefighters who have achieved 20 years of service. However, the Government Actuary's Department have previously approximated that, ignoring the effects of any tapered protection, to alter the transitional protections to only apply to firefighters who, as at 1 April 2012, were aged at least 40 and had 20 or more years pensionable service would increase the capital cost of the 1992 scheme protections by around £50 million.</p><p>Any firefighter who is within 10 years of their current Normal Pension Age, as at 1 April 2012, will remain in their existing pension scheme irrespective of length of service. A greater proportion of firefighters are protected than for any other large public service workforce.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2014-06-16T15:31:59.6254326Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61222/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61222/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-10","Fire Services: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the annual cost of maintaining existing pension provisions for firefighters (a) who have achieved 20 years of service and are within 10 years of normal retirement age and (b) who have achieved 20 years of service.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","199840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61223","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-06-16","<p> </p><p>The intention to publish a framework for action on corporate responsibility was set out in the call for views on corporate responsibility (CR) which ran during 2013. The response to the call for views was published on 28 March 2014 and this notes that the voluntary, evolving and diverse nature of CR means success relies on a business led approach. We received 152 views from a wide range of stakeholders and, where relevant, these will inform future Government action.</p><p> </p>","Cardiff Central","Jenny Willott",,"2014-06-16T15:33:59.5273331Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61223/answer","Biography information for Jenny Willott","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61223/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-06-10","Business: Ethics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he plans to publish the Government's framework for action on corporate responsibility.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","200004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61224","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-06-23","<p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This Government is committed to preventing and tackling homelessness. According to the latest publication of the Quarterly Statutory Homelessness Statistics, (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/statutory-homelessness-in-england-january-to-march-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/statutory-homelessness-in-england-january-to-march-2014</a>), homelessness remains lower than in 27 of the last 30 years.</p><p> </p><p>But we are not complacent. We have increased spending on schemes to prevent homelessness, making over £500million available to help the most vulnerable in society.</p><p>No assessment has been made of the impact of the Housing Benefit (Habitual Residence) Amendment Regulations 2014 on homelessness and rough sleeping or on victims of domestic violence and their ability to secure a place in a refuge.</p><p /> <p /> <p>EEA jobseekers have not previously been eligible for homelessness assistance and this will remain the situation.</p><p>New EEA jobseekers will still be able to get some state support, but it is right that this is limited. In such cases, adults responsible for children can claim income-based Jobseeker's Allowance for a period and in certain circumstances may be able to apply for support from the Local Authority. In particular Local Authority support is subject to statutory criteria e.g. under section 17 of the Children Act 1989 (for a child in need and their family) or section 21 of the National Assistance Act 1948 (provision of accommodation in certain circumstances).</p><p> </p><p>The Department is actively monitoring the impact of the recent changes to Housing Benefit regulations relating to EEA migrants, using Management Information and administrative data and through research with Local Authorities.</p>",,"Lord Freud","HL185 ; HL186 ; HL187","2014-06-23T14:43:39.0040423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61224/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61224/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-06-10","Housing Benefit (Habitual Residence) Amendment Regulations 2014","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the impact of the Housing Benefit (Habitual Residence) Amendment Regulations 2014 on rates of homelessness and rough sleeping.","false","Biography information for Baroness Suttie",,"Baroness Suttie","HL184"
